[Patient] How much water should I drink each day?
[Educator] Aim for about 6-8 cups of fluids daily, including water, juice, and broth.
[Patient] Can I drink soda or coffee instead?
[Educator] It's best to choose healthier options like water or herbal tea to manage fluid intake better.
[Patient] What about sports drinks for hydration?
[Educator] Sports drinks can be high in sugar and sodium, so it's best to limit them.
[Patient] How can I afford low-sodium options?
[Educator] Look for sales on canned vegetables or ask local food banks for low-sodium options.
[Patient] Should I drink more fluids if I'm feeling thirsty?
[Educator] Yes, listen to your body, but try to spread out your fluid intake throughout the day.
[Patient] What if I notice swelling in my legs?
[Educator] Contact your healthcare provider if you notice any sudden or severe swelling in your legs.
[Patient] Can I drink watermelon juice for hydration?
[Educator] Watermelon juice can be a refreshing option, but be mindful of the sugar content.
[Patient] Is it okay to drink more fluids on hot days?
[Educator] Yes, it's important to stay hydrated in hot weather, but be mindful of your overall intake.
[Patient] How can I tell if I'm drinking too much fluid?
[Educator] Watch for sudden weight gain, swelling, or shortness of breath, and contact your healthcare provider.